Incident Triage Checklist
A general-purpose checklist developed through the HTB SOC Analyst Path for triaging security alerts. Intended as a repeatable workflow for investigating common alert types.

Initial Triage

 What is the alert type and severity?
 When did the event occur? Is it ongoing?
 What asset is involved (hostname, IP, user account)?
 Is the asset critical to business operations?
 Has this alert fired before? Is there a known false positive pattern?


Context Gathering

 Pull all events related to the affected asset in the surrounding time window
 Check the user account involved — is it a service account, admin, or standard user?
 Verify the source IP reputation against threat intel feeds
 Check for related alerts on the same asset or user within the last 24-72 hours
 Review the asset's recent login history for anomalies


Investigation by Alert Type
Failed Logon / Brute Force

 How many failed attempts? Over what time period?
 Are attempts coming from a single IP or distributed sources?
 Was there an eventual successful logon?
 Did logon occur outside of normal business hours?

Suspicious Process Execution

 What is the parent process? Is the parent/child relationship expected?
 Was the process launched from an unusual directory?
 Does the command line contain encoded content or suspicious flags?
 Is the binary signed? Check hash against VirusTotal

Phishing / Malicious Email

 Did the user click any links or open attachments?
 Are there follow-on events (new processes, network connections) after email delivery?
 How many users received the same email?
 Has the sending domain been seen before?

Network Anomaly / C2 Traffic

 What is the destination IP/domain? Check reputation
 Is there a regular beaconing interval?
 What volume of data is being transferred?
 Is the traffic encrypted? Can JA3 fingerprinting identify the tool?


Escalation Criteria
Escalate immediately if any of the following are present:

Confirmed successful logon following brute force
Evidence of lateral movement to additional hosts
Active C2 communication from an internal host
Privilege escalation or new admin account creation
Data exfiltration indicators (large outbound transfers)
Ransomware indicators (mass file modification, shadow copy deletion)


Documentation

 Record timeline of events with timestamps
 Document all IOCs identified (IPs, domains, hashes, usernames)
 Note analyst actions taken during investigation
 Record escalation decision and rationale
 If closed as false positive, document why for future tuning
